<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Source for Succession Planting Seed Mixes</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Seed mixes promise easy succession planting — but most only solve part of the problem.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, Johnny’s Selected Seeds and High Mowing Organic Seeds are the best sources for succession planting seed mixes, while building your own mix from fast-maturing varieties is often the most flexible option.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Succession planting is about timing — not just seed selection. Pre-made mixes can help, but only if they are designed for staggered harvests rather than uniform growth.
  </p>
  <p>
    The best “source” depends on whether you want simplicity or control.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Picks: Best Sources for Succession Seed Mixes</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> Johnny’s Selected Seeds — strongest mix options and planning support.</li>
      <li><strong>Best organic mixes:</strong> High Mowing Organic Seeds — good selection of blended greens and fast crops.</li>
      <li><strong>Best DIY approach:</strong> build your own mixes from fast-maturing varieties.</li>
      <li><strong>Best priority overall:</strong> choose mixes that support staggered harvests, not just uniform growth.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The best results often come from combining mixes with intentional replanting — not relying on a single sowing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Most Seed Mixes Don’t Fully Solve Succession Planting</h2>

  <p>
    Many seed mixes are designed for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>visual variety (color, texture)</li>
    <li>uniform harvest timing</li>
    <li>single planting convenience</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    That works well for quick harvest crops like salad greens — but it does not automatically create staggered harvests.
  </p>

  <p>
    True succession planting still requires:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>multiple sowing dates</li>
    <li>variety timing differences</li>
    <li>intentional spacing between plantings</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Johnny’s Selected Seeds Is the Strongest Overall Source</h2>

  <p>
    Johnny’s stands out because it combines:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>high-quality seed mixes (especially greens)</li>
    <li>clear maturity timelines</li>
    <li>practical succession planting resources</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This makes it easier to use mixes as part of a broader planting strategy instead of relying on them as a standalone solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    For gardeners who want both convenience and control, this combination is hard to beat.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why High Mowing Organic Seeds Is a Strong Alternative</h2>

  <p>
    High Mowing works well for gardeners looking for organic seed mixes with good diversity and strong performance in cool and moderate climates.
  </p>

  <p>
    Their mixes are especially useful for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>salad greens</li>
    <li>quick harvest crops</li>
    <li>repeat sowings throughout the season</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Like most mixes, they still work best when paired with planned replanting.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Building Your Own Mix Is Often Better</h2>

  <p>
    Pre-made mixes are convenient, but they limit control over timing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Building your own mix allows you to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>combine varieties with different maturity speeds</li>
    <li>adjust for your climate and season length</li>
    <li>create more intentional staggered harvests</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This approach works especially well when using fast-maturing varieties from strong seed catalogs.
  </p>
</section>

